Certainly! In a LaTeX document, you can automatically generate a table of contents using the `\tableofcontents` command. Below is an example of a simple LaTeX document that includes sections and subsections, along with the necessary commands to create a table of contents.

```latex
\documentclass{article}

\begin{document}

% Title of the document
\title{Example Document with Table of Contents}
\author{Your Name}
\date{\today}
\maketitle

% Generate the table of contents
\tableofcontents

% Sections and subsections
\section{Introduction}
This is the introduction section. Here, we introduce the topic.

\section{Methodology}
In this section, we describe the methodology used in our research.

\subsection{Data Collection}
Details about data collection methods.

\subsection{Data Analysis}
Details about data analysis methods.

\section{Results}
This section presents the results of the research.

\section{Conclusion}
The conclusion summarizes the findings and implications of the research.

\end{document}
```

### Explanation of the Commands:

- `\documentclass{article}`: This command specifies the type of document you are creating (in this case, an article).
- `\title{}`, `\author{}`, and `\date{}`: These commands define the title, author, and date of the document.
- `\maketitle`: This command generates the title section of the document.
- `\tableofcontents`: This command generates the table of contents based on the sections and subsections defined in the document.
- `\section{}` and `\subsection{}`: These commands define sections and subsections in the document. They are automatically included in the table of contents.

### Compiling the Document:

To see the table of contents, you need to compile the document with LaTeX (e.g., using `pdflatex` or an equivalent tool). Note that you might need to compile the document twice to ensure that the table of contents is updated correctly with the page numbers.

